-- Mexico Stocks: America Movil, Mexichem Fall; Homebuilders Gain
-- B y   J o s e   E n r i q u e   A r r i o j a
-- 2011-12-27T22:39:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-27/mexico-stocks-america-movil-mexichem-fall-homebuilders-gain.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in Mexico trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the close of trading.  The IPC  index (MEXBOL)  fell 0.3 percent to 37,091.42.  Mexichem SAB (MEXCHEM* MM), chemical producer which has
bought more than 15 companies since 2007, said its Mexichem
Fluor unit received authorization from Mexico’s antitrust agency
to acquire Fluorita de Mexico, according to a statement to the
nation’s stock exchange. Mexichem Fluor plans to invest more
than 200 million pesos to improve operations of the company
based in the state of Coahuila. Mexichem shares fell 0.5 percent
to 44.7 pesos, its fifth consecutive day of losses.  Mexican homebuilders rose as U.S. residential real estate
prices dropped less in the year ended in October than in
September. The S&P/Case-Shiller  index  of property values in 20
cities fell 3.4 percent from October 2010 after decreasing 3.5
percent in the year ended September, the New York-based group
said today.  Desarrolladora Homex SAB (HOMEX*)  , the largest
homebuilder, advanced 4.1 percent to 38 pesos.  Consorcio ARA SA (ARA*) 
, the country’s fourth-largest homebuilder, gained for
third day to 3.93 pesos, or 3.1 percent.  Fomento Economico Mexicano SAB (FEMSAUBD MM), the owner of
 Latin America ’s largest convenience-store chain, rose 1.9
percent to 97.8 pesos, the highest price on record. “The
company is a defensive player in days of volatility,” Carlos
Calvo, an equity trader at Consultoria Internacional Casa de
Bolsa in Mexico City, said in a telephone interview. “It’s a
share that we like to start the new year.”  America Movil SAB (AMXL)  , largest wireless carrier in
the Americas, fell 0.1 percent to 15.82 pesos. The company plans
to invest as much as $5.4 billion in Brazil next year, Spanish
news agency EFE reported, citing daily Folha de Sao Paulo.  To contact the reporter on this story:
